## Examples of Good vs Bad Analysis

### BAD (what we want to avoid):

```json
{
  "issues": [
    {
      "title": "Work on the solution is slow",
      "description": "This step takes 4 hours which is 29% of total time",
      "severity": "high"
    }
  ],
  "recommendations": [
    {
      "title": "Automate Work on the solution",
      "description": "Implement automation to reduce the 4 hour cycle time"
    }
  ]
}
```

Problems with this:
- Identifies core creative work as a "problem" just because it's the longest
- Suggests "automate" for work that fundamentally requires human creativity
- Doesn't explain WHY it's a problem or what the actual issue is

### GOOD (what we want):

```json
{
  "process_summary": "13-step creative project workflow taking ~14 hours with multiple review checkpoints",
  "patterns": [
    "2 separate manager reviews (steps 6 and 9)",
    "4 client touchpoints creating external dependencies",
    "Creative work concentrated in single 4-hour block"
  ],
  "issues": [
    {
      "title": "Redundant manager reviews",
      "description": "Manager reviews the work at step 6 (tasks) and again at step 9 (solution). This may indicate unclear requirements upfront or lack of trust in the team.",
      "affected_steps": ["Review tasks by manager", "Manager reviews the solution"],
      "severity": "medium",
      "root_cause_hypothesis": "Either requirements aren't clear enough initially, or there's a culture of checking work multiple times. Both suggest opportunity for streamlining.",
      "evidence": ["2 hours total in manager reviews", "15% of total time in approvals"]
    }
  ],
  "recommendations": [
    {
      "title": "Consolidate manager reviews",
      "addresses_issue": "Redundant manager reviews",
      "description": "Combine the two manager review steps into a single more comprehensive review after the solution is implemented. Front-load requirements clarity to reduce need for task-level review.",
      "expected_benefit": "Could save ~1 hour per project and reduce wait time between reviews",
      "estimated_roi": "~$100-$150/project saved (1hr x $100-$150/hr manager time). At 20 projects/month: ~$2,000-$3,000/month.",
      "risks": ["May catch issues later in process", "Requires clearer upfront requirements"],
      "feasibility": "easy",
      "affected_steps": ["Review tasks by manager", "Manager reviews the solution"],
      "prerequisites": ["Manager buy-in", "Clear task definition template"],
      "plain_explanation": "Right now your manager checks work twice: once when tasks are assigned and again when the solution is done. Instead, skip the first check and do one thorough review at the end. To make this work, you need clearer upfront instructions so the team knows exactly what's expected. This is a process change, not a technology purchase -- cost is essentially $0 beyond the time to create a checklist.",
      "concrete_next_steps": ["Draft a one-page review checklist covering what both current reviews check for", "Run the next 2-3 projects with only the single end-of-work review as a trial", "After the trial, ask the manager and team what worked and what was missed"]
    }
  ],
  "not_problems": [
    {
      "step_name": "Work on the solution",
      "why_not_a_problem": "This is the core value-creating work. 4 hours for creative solution development is reasonable and represents actual productive time, not waste.",
      "appears_problematic_because": "It's the longest single step at 29% of total time"
    }
  ]
}
```

